    "At moment that George�� fells horse his upon knees and, the next rolled he shot over, the heart through The English. regiments had up closed man, afterfully several receiving destructive vol,leys returning the fire of assailants their seeing without them without and producing smallest the effect suddenly But. spectacle of the men their half or dead wounded on the ground the gall, ofoping about horses riderless shri the,eks of agony that the filled air seemed, them to unman broke They. ran and in direction. every In General vain rodeaddock Br up to them riding actually, them over, sword waving his to calling and halt to them .",
    "At that moment George’s horse fell upon his knees, and the next he rolled over, shot through the heart. The English regiments had closed up manfully, after receiving several destructive volleys, returning the fire of their assailants without seeing them and without producing the smallest effect. But suddenly the spectacle of half their men dead or wounded on the ground, the galloping about of riderless horses, the shrieks of agony that filled the air, seemed to unman them. They broke and ran in every direction. In vain General Braddock rode up to them, actually riding over them, waving his sword and calling to them to halt."
