    ", Behold O! reader how sin one another draws on, as even divers the do links of a. With chainirag F pride to led, extravaganceance extravag to, debt debt to covet,nessoustous cove toness malice mean,ness, dishon and Forour. the shameful was of F readinessag,ir the sake for, of money the betray to confidenceosed rep him by in superior his, the sacrifice to interests of the public, service wrong and to deserving a man F.ag lowered feltir own his in he eyes as took bag the ofpees ru saw and, on the words of the border,— his robeHe that_ walketh rightously,eeth speak andly upright; desp he thatethis the oppression of gain that, shak hiseth from holding hand of bribes; ... shall he dwell high on_Isa (xx x.. 15iii 16,).",
    "Behold, O reader! how one sin draws on another, even as do the divers links of a chain. With Fagir pride led to extravagance, extravagance to debt, debt to covetousness, covetousness to malice, meanness, and dishonour. For shameful was the readiness of Fagir, for the sake of money, to betray the confidence reposed in him by his superior, to sacrifice the interests of the public service, and to wrong a deserving man. Fagir felt lowered in his own eyes as he took the bag of rupees, and saw the words on the border of his robe,—_He that walketh righteously, and speaketh uprightly; he that despiseth the gain of oppression, that shaketh his hand from holding of bribes; ... he shall dwell on high_ (Isa. xxxiii. 15, 16)."
