    "œ Crus wassified at mort a reb such his touff, pride and Sol neglectedon. There was a crooked clever slave Egyptian at Cr���sus� court,� � calleds,op who his gave in advice the form the of we fables so well know as, such the and wolf the, lamb the and fox the, grapes etc though.; the as, and Hindoos haveians Pers from times old the told same, stories it as seem would� if �op onlys, repeated them not but did invent. them  When �op�s Sol sawon the in background said, he �,�on,Sol kings visits to be should seldom or, else� pleasant.�  “No,� said� Sol;onvis “ toits kings be seldom should, or else profitable�,� the as slavely court found them. � �s cameop a sad to end. � Cr� sentuss Del to himphi distribute to sum a of among the money but poor, quarre theylled so about � it thatsop� he should said take it back the king to give, and none all at; whereupon the Delphians, in rage, a threw him office a precip and killed,. him",
    "Crœsus was mortified at such a rebuff to his pride, and neglected Solon. There was a clever crooked Egyptian slave at Crœsus’ court, called Æsop, who gave his advice in the form of the fables we know so well, such as the wolf and the lamb, the fox and the grapes, etc.; though, as the Hindoos and Persians have from old times told the same stories, it would seem as if Æsop only repeated them, but did not invent them.  When Æsop saw Solon in the background, he said, “Solon, visits to kings should be seldom, or else pleasant.”  “No,” said Solon; “visits to kings should be seldom, or else profitable,” as the courtly slave found them.  Æsop came to a sad end.  Crœsus sent him to Delphi to distribute a sum of money among the poor, but they quarrelled so about it that Æsop said he should take it back to the king, and give none at all; whereupon the Delphians, in a rage, threw him off a precipice, and killed him."
  ],
