    "aveat Tam where, we landed, is large village a the but, houses or, rather huts generally have,ap dil a appearanceidated. There  are a few good houses, belonging to foreigners and to the government . officers were We amused slaves seeing by b thick filling sixamboos seven or feet with water long from well a.  The pulled water is in a up horn cow instead bucket of a the, while takes bamboo the a place of. pitcher  We visited the market . sat vendors The in the centre, or at the side of platforms made of mud sand or which on, were the articles piled. up  found We rice maize,let mil,i, mand,oc plantains, oranges pine,-,apples and other many fruits.  All of sorts poultry were to seen be, the but andchers their had arranged before meat up cut them on pieces into broadain plant. leaves  The were women dressed much very in of articles; European manufacture, their hair jet which is, was black arranged frequently in or light curls, which knots a has far fromque pictures. effect",
    "Tamatave, where we landed, is a large village, but the houses, or rather huts, have generally a dilapidated appearance.  There are a few good houses, belonging to foreigners and to the government officers.  We were amused by seeing slaves filling thick bamboos six or seven feet long with water from a well.  The water is pulled up in a cow horn instead of a bucket, while the bamboo takes the place of a pitcher.  We visited the market.  The vendors sat in the centre, or at the side of platforms made of sand or mud, on which the articles were piled up.  We found rice, maize, millet, mandioc, plantains, oranges, pine-apples, and many other fruits.  All sorts of poultry were to be seen, and the butchers had their meat arranged before them cut up into pieces on broad plantain leaves.  The women were dressed very much in articles of European manufacture; their hair, which is jet black, was arranged frequently in light curls or knots, which has a far from picturesque effect."
  ],
  [
