    "the west To Greeceward of mountainous lay a land b, theordered byaticri Ad, Sea and in times old Epir called. us The spoke people of a sort Greekous barbar, than worse the of thatians Macedon but the; family were royal, pure Greeks themselves believed and be to descended from Achilles; Alexander� ands� mother, Olympias been had, one of them  In. the and wars confusion that followed� upon Alexander death�s Ep, thetiro king �,�acides, took, part this led and rising to a against him, ending in his killed, being his all with family except, two little his--year,old sonr named Pyrhus who, saved by was faithful servants some. They  towards the fled of Meg city on,ara the of border,on Maced they only but reached late it night, at and there was a and rough river rapid betweenelled sw, by rains. They  called people to the on the other and, side held up the little, child the but rushing of the river voices their drowned, and their were not words . understood one last At of them peeled off a piece of from bark oak tree an and, scratched on it with of tongue the a an buckle their of account and, distress fast,ening to a it, threw stone. over it The Meg  immediatelyarians made a sort of raft with trees, and,, floating over brought Pyr littlehus andr friends his across but finding;on Maced not safe since,ander Cass had been the enemy Æ ofac,ides they went on toy Illria where, they found the king Gl,asciau with, sitting his queen. Putting the  the child on, ground they began tell to story their. the At first was unwilling king him to grant, shelter being afraid of Cass but;ander little fellow the, about crawling, came presently, near and, laying hold leg his of pulled himself, his upon feet and, looked in his up  face., The pretty unconscious action ofiant a suppl moved so Glciauas that took he in up him, arms his and gave him of those into, queen the bidding have her him bred up own among their and children; Cass thoughander offered talents 200 would, he up not give the. boy",
    "To the westward of Greece lay a mountainous land, bordered by the Adriatic Sea, and in old times called Epirus.  The people spoke a sort of barbarous Greek, worse than that of the Macedonians; but the royal family were pure Greeks, and believed themselves to be descended from Achilles; and Alexander’s mother, Olympias, had been one of them.  In the wars and confusion that followed upon Alexander’s death, the Epirot king, Æacides, took part, and this led to a rising against him, ending in his being killed, with all his family, except his little two-year-old son, named Pyrrhus, who was saved by some faithful servants.  They fled towards the city of Megara, on the border of Macedon, but they only reached it late at night, and there was a rough and rapid river between, swelled by rains.  They called to the people on the other side, and held up the little child, but the rushing of the river drowned their voices, and their words were not understood.  At last one of them peeled off a piece of bark from an oak tree, and scratched on it with the tongue of a buckle an account of their distress, and, fastening it to a stone, threw it over.  The Megarians immediately made a sort of raft with trees, and, floating over, brought little Pyrrhus and his friends across; but finding Macedon not safe, since Cassander had been the enemy of Æacides, they went on to Illyria, where they found the king, Glaucias, sitting with his queen.  Putting the child on the ground, they began to tell their story. At first the king was unwilling to grant him shelter, being afraid of Cassander; but the little fellow, crawling about, presently came near, and, laying hold of his leg, pulled himself upon his feet, and looked up in his face.  The pretty, unconscious action of a suppliant so moved Glaucias that he took him up in his arms, and gave him into those of the queen, bidding her have him bred up among their own children; and though Cassander offered 200 talents, he would not give up the boy."
  ],
