    "us now Perse understood Quicks's motiveilver for earnest soorting exhly polish him to. shield his surface In its could he safely at look the the reflection oforgon G face's. And there it--, wasthat count terrible,enance--mirrored in of the brightness, the shield the with moon overlight falling, it and all its displaying. The horror snakes, whoseous venom n not couldatures sleep, altogether themselves kept twisting the over forehead It was. fier the andcest most face horrible that seen was ever imagined or, yet and with a, strange and fearful, kind savage of beauty it in The. eyes closed, were G and theorg wason still in a sl deepumber but; there un an wasquiet expression disturbing features her, the as if was monster troubled with ugly an dream She.ashed gn herus white t, andks the into dug sand with her brazen. claws",
    "Perseus now understood Quicksilver's motive for so earnestly exhorting him to polish his shield. In its surface he could safely look at the reflection of the Gorgon's face. And there it was,--that terrible countenance,--mirrored in the brightness of the shield, with the moonlight falling over it, and displaying all its horror. The snakes, whose venomous natures could not altogether sleep, kept twisting themselves over the forehead. It was the fiercest and most horrible face that ever was seen or imagined, and yet with a strange, fearful, and savage kind of beauty in it. The eyes were closed, and the Gorgon was still in a deep slumber; but there was an unquiet expression disturbing her features, as if the monster was troubled with an ugly dream. She gnashed her white tusks, and dug into the sand with her brazen claws."
  ],
  [
    "sorry very Feeling. Mr for, Pott and Sue Bunny walked the down stairs and toward the door front hospital of the. had They done their best kind be to by to him fruit bringing him flowers. and the True, were apples green and sick the not could man eat, them but and Bunny Sue did not. know this nurses The did not tell them, for they not want did to the children feel. disappointed",
    "Feeling very sorry for Mr. Pott, Bunny and Sue walked down the stairs and toward the front door of the hospital. They had done their best to be kind to him by bringing him fruit and flowers. True, the apples were green and the sick man could not eat them, but Bunny and Sue did not know this. The nurses did not tell them, for they did not want the children to feel disappointed."
  ],
