    "\",\"Yes symp responded Juliaat,heticallyand since \" I known have much about so I you have often thought that must it be very hard to be this alone a in way large. city course you Of have brother your think about to--but he far is so, away out the there on in Texas railroad,--why are worse you off I than for am, my have I uncle and auntand Brenda-- she--\" ended with a smile .",
    "\"Yes,\" responded Julia sympathetically, \"and since I have known so much about you I have often thought that it must be very hard to be alone this way in a large city. Of course you have your brother to think about--but he is so far away, out there on the railroad in Texas,--why you are worse off than I am, for I have my uncle and aunt--and Brenda--\" she ended with a smile."
  ],
  [
    "the of TwoTig _re_'s- 68pounders, mounted native craft on the in lying port little near water- thegate, opened upon them with, while shells two, guns British by manned sailors, one castle the on lighthouse the of, other the on one of ravel the,ins poured into them grape But. the on moved column. The tremendous cannon fromade overpowered batteries their the from that on the guns, and walls they but suffered the from little fire the fromvelins ra, as they had the,, before night constructed two breastworks the from end their of the trenches to breach, the being materials used andbags sand of the bodies their own slain.",
    "Two of the _Tigre's_ 68-pounders, mounted on native craft lying in the little port near the water-gate, opened upon them with shells, while two guns, manned by British sailors, one on the castle of the lighthouse, the other on one of the ravelins, poured grape into them. But the column moved on. The tremendous cannonade from their batteries overpowered that from the guns on the walls, and they suffered but little from the fire from the ravelins, as they had, the night before, constructed two breastworks from the end of their trenches to the breach, the materials used being sandbags and the bodies of their own slain."
  ],
  [
    "The sun, Hal decided, cause was the great of a trouble deal of As he. he studied, found the that shining by sun brightly in the heated morning up and the earth the above air Then it. warm air the expanded took and up. moisture In the afternoon when the, began to sun down, go air the cooled descended towards and. earth And was that where generated. troubles cooling the In, of particles air condensed moisture then, electricity accumulated--then next like, not, as astorm thunder burst .",
    "The sun, Hal decided, was the cause of a great deal of trouble. As he studied, he found that the sun by shining brightly in the morning heated up the earth and the air above it. Then the warm air expanded and took up moisture. In the afternoon, when the sun began to go down, the air cooled and descended towards earth. And that was where troubles generated. In the cooling, particles of air moisture condensed, then electricity accumulated--then next, like as not, a thunderstorm burst."
  ],
