  [
    "May Thepole in was Wales Bedwen called because it, always was made ofch birw bed, a, tree still with associated gent theler To emotions. lover give airc a b branch,hen for is a to accept maiden his addresses; him give to collen a or, haz theel, Games reverse. various sorts of around were played bed thewen fame The. village of a its on depended not stolen being away and, were parties constantly on alert the the to steal, bedwen a feat which accomplished, when celebrated was, with festivities peculiar. This rivalry possession the for May of the waspole probably of the typical ancient idea that of first the the was May boundary day dividing of confines the summer winter and, a when place fight took powers the between of air the the, on hand striving one the to continue of winter reign, the on establish other to of summer that may Here. the cited beabinogi M Kilhw ofch Ol and wherewen, speaks it of the of daughter L Lludd Erelawint '. the wasShe most maiden splendid in the three Islands the of, Mighty and in three the,' adjacent Islands for and her does Gwyn apudd N the, fairy, king fight of every first till May the day of doom.[126] to She was the have been of bride Gwyth,yr of son the Greidaw whenl, ap Gwyn N carriedudd her off by. force The bride bereaved followedgroom, there and was a bloody struggle in, whichwyn G victorious, was which he and signal byized an of act frightful cruelty; slew he old warrior an took, out heart from his his, breast and the constrained warrior's son to eat the heart of his When father. heard of Arthur he this summonedwyn ap G Nudd before and, him deprived of him the fruits of victory his. But condemned he combatants two the to fight for maiden radiant the for henceforth on ever every May of first do tillomsday; the vict that onor possess to day the.[ maiden ]127",
    "The Maypole in Wales was called Bedwen, because it was always made of birch, bedw, a tree still associated with the gentler emotions. To give a lover a birchen branch, is for a maiden to accept his addresses; to give him a collen, or hazel, the reverse. Games of various sorts were played around the bedwen. The fame of a village depended on its not being stolen away, and parties were constantly on the alert to steal the bedwen, a feat which, when accomplished, was celebrated with peculiar festivities. This rivalry for the possession of the Maypole was probably typical of the ancient idea that the first of May was the boundary day dividing the confines of winter and summer, when a fight took place between the powers of the air, on the one hand striving to continue the reign of winter, on the other to establish that of summer. Here may be cited the Mabinogi of Kilhwch and Olwen, where it speaks of the daughter of Lludd Llaw Ereint. 'She was the most splendid maiden in the three Islands of the Mighty, and in the three Islands adjacent,' and for her does Gwyn ap Nudd, the fairy king, fight every first of May till the day of doom.[126] She was to have been the bride of Gwythyr, the son of Greidawl, when Gwyn ap Nudd carried her off by force. The bereaved bridegroom followed, and there was a bloody struggle, in which Gwyn was victorious, and which he signalized by an act of frightful cruelty; he slew an old warrior, took out his heart from his breast, and constrained the warrior's son to eat the heart of his father. When Arthur heard of this he summoned Gwyn ap Nudd before him, and deprived him of the fruits of his victory. But he condemned the two combatants to fight for the radiant maiden henceforth for ever on every first of May till doomsday; the victor on that day to possess the maiden.[127]"
  ],
