    "it did What She matter? it had known before. all She had said very words those. But herself had thought sheshe-- had been that sure did people other understand not it way that. perhaps Well, most people did. not No, that was. nonsense Lilian had Day a position achieved prominence in of purely her class a remarkable through alert toness sentiment public.ayson P Margaret a girl, of a very much and different type finer, for stood the best of that. sentiment Eleanor had admired often her her for-sighted clear and goodness judgment They. un said haditatinghesly that was she; failure a then the college so. thought it Well, was Jean East faultman's, and then Caroline,'s Wales Betty and N.'s!onsense it her own was. she Should in go off leave June and name spelling her her behind failure should Or? back she come somehow change and failure to the Could? success ? she",
    "What did it matter? She had known it all before. She had said those very words herself. But she had thought--she had been sure that other people did not understand it that way. Well, perhaps most people did not. No, that was nonsense. Lilian Day had achieved a position of prominence in her class purely through a remarkable alertness to public sentiment. Margaret Payson, a girl of a very different and much finer type, stood for the best of that sentiment. Eleanor had often admired her for her clear-sightedness and good judgment. They had said unhesitatingly that she was a failure; then the college thought so. Well, it was Jean Eastman's fault then, and Caroline's, and Betty Wales's. Nonsense! it was her own. Should she go off in June and leave her name spelling failure behind her? Or should she come back and somehow change the failure to success? Could she?"
  ],
