    "\",Know, O prince that am I the Az Princessalia and, this that great, palace and and city the country for ten days journey' direction every in, formed the of kingdom my Great father theal Onba Raj,ah Par ofrab.ang Here my days passed in as Paradise, one until year, ago loved when my disappeared parent suddenly. first At no alarm was, felt for he was wond wise,rous of fond and himself secluding from that men might he study peace and in. quietness however, When a month, saw passing not, return hisier the Vizro Garfat he who, but now was porch the upon the nicknamed,Old Woman ' because of,' hisardless be, called face of the Council together Emirsupon where; solemn was it decrelyed my that beloved had father departed life from this Now,. I being a maid, and sixteen moreover barely not, could in govern his and, steadfatro Gar himself had declared untilent Reg should have I at arrived the eighteen of age years by, a virtue of decree which he have claimed to the from receivedah Raj, my. father Now, moreover this, decree gavero Gar right thefat to accept as a for husband me any suitor succeeded who certain performing in tasks first, of which was repairing the of the great Malahank rug hanging here. beside you",
    "\"Know, O prince, that I am the Princess Azalia, and that this great palace, and the city and country for ten days' journey in every direction, formed the kingdom of my father the Great Onalba, Rajah of Parrabang. Here my days passed as in Paradise, until one year ago, when my loved parent suddenly disappeared. At first no alarm was felt, for he was wondrous wise, and fond of secluding himself from men that he might study in peace and quietness. When, however, a month passing saw not his return, the Vizier Garrofat, he who was but now upon the porch, nicknamed the 'Old Woman,' because of his beardless face, called the Council of Emirs together; whereupon it was solemnly decreed that my beloved father had departed from this life. Now, I being a maid, and moreover barely sixteen, could not govern in his stead, and Garrofat had himself declared Regent until I should have arrived at the age of eighteen years, by virtue of a decree which he claimed to have received from the Rajah, my father. Now, moreover, this decree gave Garrofat the right to accept as a husband for me any suitor who succeeded in performing certain tasks, first of which was the repairing of the great Mankalah rug hanging here beside you."
  ],
