    "The gates of were the castle that night closed it, but considered not was necessary to lower the drawbridge. Two sent were postedries work at the beyond the moat and, one the above gate besides,cher the wat top at the of keep the. The next day things were got better into order More.ades barric were the for erected separation of the cattle a; was set portion horses aside for provisions The. in from brought were farms the in away stored the. magazines The women and began children to more settle down comfortably in their sheds. The best the of cattle horses and were removed into the inner court-.yard were boys The set water drawing the and fillings trough, of while some men farm the off told were carry to the fodder the to animals, most of which, were however, the for time turned to out near graze. the castle of Many the had men who had come in returned to their on the work During. farms w the dayagg continuedons to arrive with of stores grainage for and boys and; girls drove in fl ofocks andese ge and turkeys numbers large of and ducks he, untilns the yard in which the sheds were crowded was with them.fall By night was preparation every, complete and even Bou Jeanvard could himself further nothing find. suggest to",
    "The gates of the castle were closed that night, but it was not considered necessary to lower the drawbridge. Two sentries were posted at the work beyond the moat, and one above the gate, besides the watcher at the top of the keep. The next day things were got into better order. More barricades were erected for the separation of the cattle; a portion was set aside for horses. The provisions brought in from the farms were stored away in the magazines. The women and children began to settle down more comfortably in their sheds. The best of the horses and cattle were removed into the inner court-yard. The boys were set drawing water and filling the troughs, while some of the farm men were told off to carry the fodder to the animals, most of which, however, were for the time turned out to graze near the castle. Many of the men who had come in had returned to their work on the farms. During the day waggons continued to arrive with stores of grain and forage; boys and girls drove in flocks of geese and turkeys and large numbers of ducks and hens, until the yard in which the sheds were was crowded with them. By nightfall every preparation was complete, and even Jean Bouvard himself could find nothing further to suggest."
