    "on board Returning, stood we north,ward might we that view obtain a of coast the we sailed as. along  and I Dick on remained deck all morning the At.  we last sightoo Led, thee first town we seen had onish the Corn coast. oo Le stands at the a of mouth, valley at of bottom the a which runs . stream It of consists West East and Looe--romanticlooking- foreign places.  houses The are irregular together grouped withly,ashedew whit stairs walls, green outside, roofs grey and g,ables with myrtles ger,,aniums other and plants warm of a in climate flourishing their. midst L West  isooe chiefly inhabited by fishermen, their c humbleott scatteredages being without about any respect order to However., but obtained we view a distant of it.",
    "Returning on board, we stood northward, that we might obtain a view of the coast as we sailed along.  Dick and I remained on deck all the morning.  At last we sighted Looe, the first town we had seen on the Cornish coast.  Looe stands at the mouth of a valley, at the bottom of which runs a stream.  It consists of East and West Looe--romantic foreign-looking places.  The houses are grouped together irregularly, with whitewashed walls, stairs outside, green roofs and grey gables, with myrtles, geraniums, and other plants of a warm climate flourishing in their midst.  West Looe is inhabited chiefly by fishermen, their humble cottages being scattered about without any respect to order. However, we obtained but a distant view of it."
  ],
