    "The day next 31 the, Octoberst of53, 17, George set on his forth missionous ardu had He. him before nearly miles six hundred, travelling of it of much an un through wilderness,broken where snow and rain ice and hail at and were season that expected be to the In. conference the with his and governor advisers, which after lasted until, George midnight been given had _ecartanche bl_ his selecting in, escort which not was to seven persons exceed reached until hestown, Log could when he as many take as he Indians thought. wise He made quickly mind his up as whom to. he wanted He wished first of a person breeding gentle as an interpreter between the and himself officers. French He remembered Captain Vanbra Jacob,am a, officer Dutch retired now, and living atburg Fredericks who, might be to induced the make journey. Then there G wereist Davidson John and was It. thought, best, however to Indian take an along interpreter as for Indians the they, as complain, might in case of, misunderstanding a that had Davidson. fooled them to regard In three the other persons concluded George that it would to well be until wait he Green reachedway Court which, was in directly route the of his journey outward as, he would be most to likely find that vicinity in better person a used to such than expedition an the in lower. Armed country credentials with full by governor the with, and a belt around body his containing a sum large and gold inot negiable, George bills took daylight at the road he had traversed the night before .",
    "The next day, the 31st of October, 1753, George set forth on his arduous mission. He had before him nearly six hundred miles of travelling, much of it through an unbroken wilderness, where snow and ice and rain and hail at that season were to be expected. In the conference with the governor and his advisers, which lasted until after midnight, George had been given _carte blanche_ in selecting his escort, which was not to exceed seven persons until he reached Logstown, when he could take as many Indians as he thought wise. He quickly made up his mind as to whom he wanted. He wished first a person of gentle breeding as an interpreter between himself and the French officers. He remembered Captain Jacob Vanbraam, a Dutch officer, now retired, and living at Fredericksburg, who might be induced to make the journey. Then there were Gist and John Davidson. It was thought best, however, to take an Indian along as interpreter for the Indians, as they might complain, in case of a misunderstanding, that Davidson had fooled them. In regard to the other three persons George concluded that it would be well to wait until he reached Greenway Court, which was directly in the route of his outward journey, as he would be most likely to find in that vicinity a person better used to such an expedition than in the lower country. Armed with full credentials by the governor, and with a belt around his body containing a large sum in gold and negotiable bills, George at daylight took the road he had traversed the night before."
