    "above The childrenmentioned,- as being full as life of they hold could overflowing, kept porch from theangle T ofwood, andpering scam along the- gravel, orwalk rushing across thewy de her the ofbage. I lawn can hardly tell how many of small people these there were; not less than or nine ten however,, nor more than dozen a, all sorts of,, sizes and, ages girls whether or boys. They were, brothers, sisters and, together cousins with a few their of young, acquaintances who been had invited Mr. by. Mrs andingle Pr to spend of some delightful weather this their own with at children Tanglewood. am I afraid you to tell, names their to or even any them give names other which have children ever been called by; because, to certain my, knowledge authors get sometimes themselves great into trouble giving accidentally by of names the to persons real the in characters. their books For reason this I to mean call Prim them Per,roseinkle,iw Sweet, Fernandelion D, Blue Eye Clover,,berry Huckle C,owslip, SquBl-ash,ossom Milk Plant,weedain and,cup; Butter although, to sure, be such might titles better a suit fair of group a thanies company of earthly children.",
    "The children above-mentioned, being as full of life as they could hold, kept overflowing from the porch of Tanglewood, and scampering along the gravel-walk, or rushing across the dewy herbage of the lawn. I can hardly tell how many of these small people there were; not less than nine or ten, however, nor more than a dozen, of all sorts, sizes, and ages, whether girls or boys. They were brothers, sisters, and cousins, together with a few of their young acquaintances, who had been invited by Mr. and Mrs. Pringle to spend some of this delightful weather with their own children at Tanglewood. I am afraid to tell you their names, or even to give them any names which other children have ever been called by; because, to my certain knowledge, authors sometimes get themselves into great trouble by accidentally giving the names of real persons to the characters in their books. For this reason I mean to call them Primrose, Periwinkle, Sweet Fern, Dandelion, Blue Eye, Clover, Huckleberry, Cowslip, Squash-Blossom, Milkweed, Plantain, and Buttercup; although, to be sure, such titles might better suit a group of fairies than a company of earthly children."
  ],
